</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FF9D67320100243BFC67FEA6" authority="Kozar &amp; Konczne Benedicty 2008: 119 - 121" authorityName="Kozar &amp; Konczne Benedicty" authorityPageNumber="119 - 121" authorityYear="2008" box="[307,970,256,279]" class="Insecta" family="Eriococcidae" genus="Coxicoccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foldi">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D67320100243BFE4BFEA6" box="[307,486,256,279]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Coxicoccus foldi</emphasis>
Kozár &amp; Konczné Benedicty 2008: 119–121
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B87B36C7FF9D673200A42471FB3DFD4E" blockId="41.[151,1436,330,1215]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D673200A42471FDFCFED5" bold="true" box="[151,593,330,356]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Generic diagnosis. Adult female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="20FF2A42FF9D673202562471FD6AFED5" box="[613,711,330,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="42.[151,257,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[211,1382,183,1741]" captionTargetId="figure-88@42.[188,1399,177,1756]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 18. Coxicoccus foldi Kozár &amp; Konczné Benedicty. Adult female, where A = dorsal spinose seta; B = dorsal microtubular duct; D = dorsal macrotubular duct; G = dorsal view of anal plate; J, J1, J2 = ventral setae; L = ventral loculate pore; R = marginal spinose seta; V = antenna, and W= claw of mesothoracic leg (modified after Kozár &amp; Konczné Benedicty, 2008)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5313389" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5313389/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D673202D12471FCFDFED2" box="[738,848,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Dorsum.</emphasis>
With spine-like setae of more or less 1 size. Macrotubular ducts narrow, long, inner ductule ending in flower-like terminal gland; present throughout. Microtubular ducts long with bifurcate orifice, few but often associated with base of dorsal spinose setae. Anal lobes well developed, dorsal surface with 3 strong, curved spinose setae. Anal ring sclerotised, not well developed, with 8 setae, each twice as long as width of anal ring; anal ring pores few. Median plate absent. 
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D673200A4273EFF58FDAF" box="[151,245,517,542]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Margin.</emphasis>
Not differentiated. 
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D673201EE273EFD9DFDAF" box="[477,560,517,542]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Venter.</emphasis>
Setae capitate on posterior abdominal segment; suranal setae also capitate and longer than length of anal lobes; ventral surface of each anal lobe with 1 short apical seta + a capitate subapical seta. Macrotubular ducts sparse throughout. Microtubular ducts submarginal. Cruciform pores absent. Loculate pores present medially, mainly on abdomen. Antennae 7 segmented. Frontal lobes and antennal tubercles absent. Labium 1 (?) segmented; basal segment with 1 pair setae. Legs long, tibia shorter than tarsus; all coxae with spinulae; metacoxae with small translucent pores. Vulva present between abdominal segments VII and VIII. (Modified after Kozár &amp; Konczné Benedicty, 2008).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B87B36C7FF9D673200F52631FE11FC95" blockId="41.[151,1436,330,1215]" box="[198,444,778,804]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Host plant unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F0DE654CFF9D673200F52614FD7AFB0E" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B87B36C7FF9D673200F52614FDC8FBC5" blockId="41.[151,1436,330,1215]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D673200F52614FEE4FCF8" bold="true" box="[198,329,815,841]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Comment.</emphasis>
Kozár &amp; Konczné Benedicty (2008) state that this genus is close to 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FF9D673204EE260BFACCFCF8" authorityName="Targioni Tozzetti" authorityYear="1868" box="[1245,1377,816,841]" class="Insecta" family="Eriococcidae" genus="Eriococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D673204EE260BFACCFCF8" box="[1245,1377,816,841]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Eriococcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FF9D673200A4266EFEFDFCDF" box="[151,336,853,878]" class="Florideophyceae" family="Cystocloniaceae" genus="Acanthococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gigartinales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D673200A4266EFEFDFCDF" box="[151,336,853,878]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Acanthococcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It resembles 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FF9D67320232266EFD27FCDF" authorityName="Targioni Tozzetti" authorityYear="1868" box="[513,650,853,878]" class="Insecta" family="Eriococcidae" genus="Eriococcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D67320232266EFD27FCDF" box="[513,650,853,878]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Eriococcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having: (i) only 1 seta on basal segment of labium; (ii) long microtubular ducts with a bifurcate orifice; and (iii) in lacking cruciform pores. It differs in: (i) absence of enlarged tubular ducts; (ii) absence of frontal lobes; and (iii) presence of translucent pores on metacoxa, femur and tibia. It resembles 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FF9D6732019626FEFDFAFC6F" box="[421,599,965,990]" class="Florideophyceae" family="Cystocloniaceae" genus="Acanthococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gigartinales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FF9D6732019626FEFDFAFC6F" box="[421,599,965,990]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Acanthococcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having: (i) enlarged spine-like setae on dorsum; and (ii) micro- and macrotubular ducts; it differs in the absence of: (i) cruciform pores; (ii) frontal lobes; and (iii) a median plate, and presence of (iv) only 1 pair of setae on basal segment of labium. In addition, it differs from both genera in having clavate setae posteriorly on the venter. Note that the vulva lies between VII and VIII, not as illustrated in Kozár &amp; Konczné Benedicty (2008).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B87B36C7FF9D673200F521BBFD7AFB0E" blockId="41.[151,1436,330,1215]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
